00:01:28.584 --> 00:01:29.500
PROFESSOR: Absolutely.

00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:32.300
PHILIP TAN: OK, so today,
what we're going to do

00:01:32.300 --> 00:01:36.860
is talk a little bit about
aesthetics, about what we

00:01:36.860 --> 00:01:38.630
mean when we say
we want your game

00:01:38.630 --> 00:01:40.450
to have a cohesive aesthetic.

00:01:40.450 --> 00:01:43.130
We do realize that the games
that we're asking you to make

00:01:43.130 --> 00:01:45.340
are extremely time constrained.

00:01:45.340 --> 00:01:49.800
We've been asking you not to go
terribly much beyond the scope

00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:51.270
of what you've done before.

00:01:51.270 --> 00:01:53.500
But what we want
to see in your game

00:01:53.500 --> 00:01:57.400
is a really, really
cohesive aesthetic.

00:01:57.400 --> 00:01:59.310
We used to tell
students that we wanted

00:01:59.310 --> 00:02:01.640
them to put out polished games.

00:02:01.640 --> 00:02:05.080
But there was a really
unclear definition

00:02:05.080 --> 00:02:08.350
when we used to do this about
what a polished game would be.

00:02:08.350 --> 00:02:12.790
And we also realized
that for some students,

00:02:12.790 --> 00:02:16.200
for a lot of you, you've seen
games that are really, really,

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:18.100
really polished.

00:02:18.100 --> 00:02:21.160
When I say a polished
game, can you

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:23.410
come up with some
examples of things

00:02:23.410 --> 00:02:24.803
that immediately come to mind?

00:02:24.803 --> 00:02:25.670
STUDENT: Limbo.

00:02:25.670 --> 00:02:26.420
PHILIP TAN: Limbo?

00:02:26.420 --> 00:02:28.000
Yeah, that's the
black and white side

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.600
scrolling platform, really,
really spooky, gorgeous visuals

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:33.890
and sound design.

00:02:33.890 --> 00:02:34.520
What else?

00:02:37.884 --> 00:02:38.384
Yeah.

00:02:38.384 --> 00:02:40.249
STUDENT: All of the
Final Fantasy games

00:02:40.249 --> 00:02:41.290
have really polished UIs.

00:02:41.290 --> 00:02:42.810
PHILIP TAN: Pretty much, yeah.

00:02:42.810 --> 00:02:45.250
Every single Final
Fantasy game for its era

00:02:45.250 --> 00:02:47.890
is probably like the high
watermark for production

00:02:47.890 --> 00:02:50.870
values-- not just the UI.

00:02:50.870 --> 00:02:53.820
But you're right in
saying the UI is alive.

00:02:53.820 --> 00:02:56.390
Whenever you even switch
to a different menu option,

00:02:56.390 --> 00:02:57.688
it does this little animation.

00:02:57.688 --> 00:02:59.604
STUDENT: It's one of the
only [INAUDIBLE] that

00:02:59.604 --> 00:03:00.771
has a really good UI design.

00:03:00.771 --> 00:03:02.229
And I've looked at
a bunch of them.

00:03:02.229 --> 00:03:04.452
And it's like, Final
Fantasy is just way

00:03:04.452 --> 00:03:05.635
better than all that stuff.

00:03:05.635 --> 00:03:06.110
And of course,
the graphics, too.

00:03:06.110 --> 00:03:08.276
PHILIP TAN: Which is amazing,
because they change it

00:03:08.276 --> 00:03:09.526
so much every game.

00:03:09.526 --> 00:03:10.900
Unlike a lot of
other franchises,

00:03:10.900 --> 00:03:13.110
they change the formula
a lot, but also of course

00:03:13.110 --> 00:03:15.120
other things, like
the animation quality

00:03:15.120 --> 00:03:17.430
and the music and
the voice act--

00:03:17.430 --> 00:03:20.486
maybe not the voice acting.

00:03:20.486 --> 00:03:20.986
Yeah.

00:03:20.986 --> 00:03:22.410
STUDENT: Meat Boy.

00:03:22.410 --> 00:03:23.535
PHILIP TAN: Super Meat Boy?

00:03:23.535 --> 00:03:24.865
STUDENT: Yeah.

00:03:24.865 --> 00:03:26.780
[INAUDIBLE] physics.

00:03:26.780 --> 00:03:30.470
PHILIP TAN: Yeah, for folks
who haven't played this game,

00:03:30.470 --> 00:03:32.050
it's a really punishing game.

00:03:32.050 --> 00:03:34.980
But it makes it super
easy for you to try again.

00:03:34.980 --> 00:03:38.410
In fact, there's like a
single frame between you dying

00:03:38.410 --> 00:03:41.430
and you starting the game again.

00:03:41.430 --> 00:03:43.440
And it goes right off.

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:47.040
A game built by two people, by
the way-- it's an indie game.

00:03:47.040 --> 00:03:49.990
You can see it in documentaries
like Indie Game-- The Movie.

00:03:49.990 --> 00:03:52.970
And you can see even though
they're working on their own--

00:03:52.970 --> 00:03:54.950
and they do spend a
considerable amount of time

00:03:54.950 --> 00:03:58.670
on an extremely visually
polished and musically amazing

00:03:58.670 --> 00:03:59.697
game as well.

00:03:59.697 --> 00:04:00.980
STUDENT: Monument Valley

00:04:00.980 --> 00:04:03.080
PHILIP TAN: Monument
Valley for the iOS?

00:04:03.080 --> 00:04:05.460
Yeah, I can't remember, has
it come out for Android yet?

00:04:05.460 --> 00:04:08.410
But it's definitely
iOS right now.

00:04:08.410 --> 00:04:11.204
But what strikes
you as polished?

00:04:11.204 --> 00:04:16.180
STUDENT: The graphics and the
gameplay is just very smooth.

00:04:16.180 --> 00:04:17.680
PHILIP TAN: Mhm,
and the game's kind

00:04:17.680 --> 00:04:21.664
of like a flat shaded
isometric game,

00:04:21.664 --> 00:04:23.590
if you're familiar
with that 3D concept.

00:04:23.590 --> 00:04:25.190
It means that things
that are far away

00:04:25.190 --> 00:04:27.315
are the same size as things
that are close to you--

00:04:27.315 --> 00:04:31.140
isometric orthogonal projection.

00:04:31.140 --> 00:04:34.870
The camera is kind of looking at
the world at a 45 degree angle

00:04:34.870 --> 00:04:37.999
up and sideways.

00:04:37.999 --> 00:04:40.540
Everything's flat shaded, but
it's got incredible art design.

00:04:40.540 --> 00:04:45.000
It's got art direction,
I would say, just

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:47.570
how all of the characters,
even though they basically all

00:04:47.570 --> 00:04:51.150
have one color, maybe
black and white,

00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:53.300
move with a lot
of expressiveness.

00:04:53.300 --> 00:04:56.000
They have iconic characters,
and you immediately

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.400
sort of recognize what each
character is supposed to be,

00:04:58.400 --> 00:05:00.233
even though the game
is pretty much made out

00:05:00.233 --> 00:05:02.760
of geometric shapes.

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:04.330
I call out Hearthstone.

00:05:04.330 --> 00:05:05.310
Anyone playing that?

00:05:05.310 --> 00:05:05.820
Anyone else?

00:05:05.820 --> 00:05:10.160
Yeah, it's like just every
little bit of movement

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:12.870
that the screen does as
soon as your finger touches

00:05:12.870 --> 00:05:15.650
that screen is amazing.

00:05:15.650 --> 00:05:17.580
Even little silly
things, like when

00:05:17.580 --> 00:05:19.400
you are looking for
a match, and you

00:05:19.400 --> 00:05:21.540
see all the other
people who you could

00:05:21.540 --> 00:05:23.000
have been matched against.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.830
And it of course always selects
the perfect match for you.

00:05:25.830 --> 00:05:27.370
It's a ridiculous
little UI thing.

00:05:27.370 --> 00:05:28.870
But it sort of gets
you in the mood.

00:05:28.870 --> 00:05:30.620
And of course, that's
like music and stuff

00:05:30.620 --> 00:05:34.670
for what's really a card game,
a collectible card game, right?

00:05:34.670 --> 00:05:40.140
So what I'd like to do right
now is play through a game

00:05:40.140 --> 00:05:42.910
that I feel has a
coherent aesthetic.

00:05:42.910 --> 00:05:45.570
But maybe you wouldn't
necessarily call it polished.

00:05:45.570 --> 00:05:47.310
But it gets you a
little bit closer

00:05:47.310 --> 00:05:49.187
to what we're looking at.

00:05:49.187 --> 00:05:51.770
Because it might be a little bit
more feasible for this class.

