00:50:48.570 --> 00:50:49.403
as long as you want.

00:50:49.403 --> 00:50:50.270
But nothing happens.

00:50:50.270 --> 00:50:52.810
And then as soon as you
jump off, the music starts.

00:50:52.810 --> 00:50:55.990
So it's like, all right, now
you're doing something that you

00:50:55.990 --> 00:50:58.317
should feel excited about.

00:50:58.317 --> 00:51:00.400
So we're going to play
this exciting music at you.

00:51:02.816 --> 00:51:04.940
STUDENT: You can hear the
air while you're falling.

00:51:04.940 --> 00:51:08.090
PHILIP TAN: Yeah, there's a very
strong sort of rushing sound.

00:51:08.090 --> 00:51:10.710
And you're getting
other UI sounds as well.

00:51:10.710 --> 00:51:13.840
Those are the things that
are actually giving you

00:51:13.840 --> 00:51:15.580
points, getting close
to other buildings.

00:51:15.580 --> 00:51:17.680
And so there's some
visual feedback.

00:51:17.680 --> 00:51:20.474
STUDENT: The game menu before
it starts is really confusing.

00:51:20.474 --> 00:51:21.640
There was just way too much.

00:51:21.640 --> 00:51:23.630
I don't think that
was working at all.

00:51:23.630 --> 00:51:27.110
PHILIP TAN: Yeah, the thing is
I've played a bit of this game.

00:51:27.110 --> 00:51:31.760
So it normally directs
you to the first thing

00:51:31.760 --> 00:51:33.210
that you can click
really clearly.

00:51:33.210 --> 00:51:35.050
And then at some
point of time, it

00:51:35.050 --> 00:51:39.119
stops leading you
to a linear path.

00:51:39.119 --> 00:51:41.160
So you've got this whole
grid of different things

00:51:41.160 --> 00:51:42.560
that you can do to choose one.

00:51:42.560 --> 00:51:46.920
So admittedly, the
game UI may not

00:51:46.920 --> 00:51:48.390
achieve what it's trying to do.

00:51:48.390 --> 00:51:51.230
But what do you think
it's trying to do,

00:51:51.230 --> 00:51:54.260
even if it fails at it?

00:51:54.260 --> 00:51:56.700
It's sort of like, here's
this ridiculous grid

00:51:56.700 --> 00:52:00.160
of all of these different
things that you can do.

00:52:00.160 --> 00:52:02.380
But maybe some of them are
unlocked, or some of them

00:52:02.380 --> 00:52:06.330
are still locked and some
things are still locked out.

00:52:06.330 --> 00:52:08.470
What's the point of showing
you all these things

00:52:08.470 --> 00:52:11.180
that you can't do?

00:52:11.180 --> 00:52:13.180
STUDENT: Try and motivate
you to unlock them

00:52:13.180 --> 00:52:14.180
so that you can do them.

00:52:14.180 --> 00:52:17.070
PHILIP TAN: Right,
this whole idea

00:52:17.070 --> 00:52:20.370
is that-- it's the
same idea in Zelda.

00:52:20.370 --> 00:52:22.490
Sometimes you see this
heart in a location

00:52:22.490 --> 00:52:24.730
which you know that you
can't actually get to yet.

00:52:24.730 --> 00:52:28.480
But the whole point of that is
to make you want to get there.

00:52:28.480 --> 00:52:31.560
And that's what the unlock
system in this game, I believe,

00:52:31.560 --> 00:52:33.310
is trying to do.

00:52:33.310 --> 00:52:36.462
It wants to give you an
incentive to keep playing.

00:52:36.462 --> 00:52:38.045
Because there's all
this other content

00:52:38.045 --> 00:52:39.350
that you haven't seen yet.

00:52:39.350 --> 00:52:42.129
But you kind of have a
clue that it's out there.

00:52:42.129 --> 00:52:43.670
At the beginning of
the game, there's

00:52:43.670 --> 00:52:46.044
a little narration actually
that you may not have caught.

00:52:46.044 --> 00:52:50.110
It says, the city of Boston
has outlawed base jumping,

00:52:50.110 --> 00:52:51.950
so this whole idea
that what you're doing

00:52:51.950 --> 00:52:54.280
isn't actually sanctioned
by the authorities.

00:52:54.280 --> 00:52:56.810
And eventually, you get
these commands later

00:52:56.810 --> 00:53:01.332
where you can flip off
people while you jump off,

00:53:01.332 --> 00:53:02.790
unless they happen
to be your fans.

00:53:02.790 --> 00:53:04.248
And then you give
them a thumbs up.

00:53:06.690 --> 00:53:14.140
So there's a sense that what
you're doing isn't advisable.

00:53:14.140 --> 00:53:18.730
This is not supposed to be
just how the future looks like.

00:53:18.730 --> 00:53:22.170
Even in this weird future where
you have these mega skyscrapers

00:53:22.170 --> 00:53:26.146
that go all the way into space,
this is still not a good idea.

00:53:26.146 --> 00:53:27.520
But you're going
to do it anyway.

00:53:27.520 --> 00:53:30.220
That's what this game is about.

00:53:30.220 --> 00:53:33.350
So it's a 3D game.

00:53:33.350 --> 00:53:35.650
This one was done
in Unity, actually,

00:53:35.650 --> 00:53:38.390
although it was on port from
a game that wasn't originally

00:53:38.390 --> 00:53:39.280
developed in Unity.

00:53:39.280 --> 00:53:41.550
So you think of the
very first version,

00:53:41.550 --> 00:53:45.340
which is just called
AaaaaAAaaaAAAaaAAAAaAAAAA!!!--

00:53:45.340 --> 00:53:47.390
A Reckless Disregard
for Gravity.

00:53:47.390 --> 00:53:48.080
Is that right?

00:53:48.080 --> 00:53:48.580
Yeah.

00:53:48.580 --> 00:53:51.010
That game only runs on Windows.

00:53:51.010 --> 00:53:53.410
And all the versions
that have come since then

00:53:53.410 --> 00:53:54.990
have all run on
multiple platforms.

00:53:54.990 --> 00:53:56.531
Because they were
developed on Unity.

00:53:56.531 --> 00:53:57.880
STUDENT: Including Oculus Rift.

00:53:57.880 --> 00:53:58.940
PHILIP TAN: Including Oculus
Rift, an Oculus Rift version

00:53:58.940 --> 00:54:00.460
of that game.

00:54:00.460 --> 00:54:02.700
You can imagine how
that would work.

00:54:02.700 --> 00:54:08.850
Anyway, so something that
I want to end on today--

00:54:08.850 --> 00:54:12.320
there's a second
presentation very quickly.

00:54:12.320 --> 00:54:13.320
Actually, you know what?

00:54:13.320 --> 00:54:14.770
I've been talking for an hour.

00:54:14.770 --> 00:54:16.548
Let's take a quick break.

00:54:16.548 --> 00:54:22.500
And we'll come back
in 2:15, 10 minutes.

00:54:22.500 --> 00:54:25.540
All right, let me
see, am I on mute?

00:54:25.540 --> 00:54:28.680
OK, so what I'm
going to do now is

00:54:28.680 --> 00:54:32.340
I'm going to have
your groups actually

00:54:32.340 --> 00:54:36.390
have a discussion about what you
want your game mechanics to do.

00:54:36.390 --> 00:54:38.280
And the reason for
this is because I

00:54:38.280 --> 00:54:41.730
feel that a lot of you
probably are decently equipped

00:54:41.730 --> 00:54:45.470
to talk about what you want your
story lines and your characters

00:54:45.470 --> 00:54:49.360
or your art style or your sound
design to achieve in your game.

00:54:49.360 --> 00:54:51.950
And the reason for that is
we've seen a lot of movies.

00:54:51.950 --> 00:54:54.910
We know how we react to music.

00:54:54.910 --> 00:54:58.520
We realize what visuals have
on sort of human emotion.

00:54:58.520 --> 00:55:00.880
But I'm not sure if you've
had this discussion yet

00:55:00.880 --> 00:55:03.940
in your team about what you
want your mechanics to do

00:55:03.940 --> 00:55:04.740
aesthetically.

00:55:04.740 --> 00:55:07.090
What kind of
experience do you want

00:55:07.090 --> 00:55:09.100
to generate for the player?

00:55:09.100 --> 00:55:12.231
So really, it's what you want
everything in your game to do.

00:55:12.231 --> 00:55:14.230
But right now, I'm asking
you to do a discussion

00:55:14.230 --> 00:55:17.820
about what you specifically
want your games to do.

00:55:17.820 --> 00:55:19.372
I'm going to throw
some words at you

00:55:19.372 --> 00:55:23.320
to help you be able to frame
these ideas inside your team.

00:55:23.320 --> 00:55:24.842
First is that, is this a game?

00:55:24.842 --> 00:55:27.050
How many of you feel like
you're making a game that's

00:55:27.050 --> 00:55:32.760
kind of about strategically
outwitting the game system,

00:55:32.760 --> 00:55:34.930
being smarter than the
computer, basically,

00:55:34.930 --> 00:55:38.080
or being smarter than
the game designer, that's

00:55:38.080 --> 00:55:41.150
how you win the game?

00:55:41.150 --> 00:55:43.380
How many of you feel
like your game is really

00:55:43.380 --> 00:55:46.840
about some random thing
happens, and now you

00:55:46.840 --> 00:55:49.080
have to deal with it?

00:55:49.080 --> 00:55:53.210
OK I see a couple, a few,
hands out there, maybe.

00:55:53.210 --> 00:55:54.970
And some of you don't
know where your game

00:55:54.970 --> 00:55:57.810
falls in that spectrum.

00:55:57.810 --> 00:56:02.835
Of course, it could be
a bit of both, right?

00:56:02.835 --> 00:56:06.170
A French writer named
Roger Caillois came up

00:56:06.170 --> 00:56:09.822
with a categorization of what
these different kinds of game

00:56:09.822 --> 00:56:11.920
play could be termed.

